The fact of generally just and moderate government is admitted and indisputable. We are told ol constant consultation of the senate, even on matters not strictly belonging to their cognizance¹; and its chief members are encouraged to discuss, and rebuked for servility² ; that the office of the magistrates of the republic is respected⁸; the laws, with one exception ⁶, uprightly administered ; thatin the bestowal of dignities the worthiest were selected; that Tiberius set an example of frugality, both in the moderate siae and number of his Italian estates, amid the vast villas of the nobles ⁵, and in unostentatious management and retinue3 as well as an example of moderatiori in conducting disputes with other citizens as between equals in the law-courts. Itis further admitted that these characteristics at home were accompanied by clemency and vigilance abroad: that no new burdens were laid on the provinces ; the old ones adjusted with care and remitted on occasion; personal ,violence and confiscation scrupulously avoided; crnelty and extortion in govemors duly punished; fiscal procuratorships conferred on men of character, even without personal ltnotvledge5 and their tenure indefinitely emended, as if to diminish temptation to peculation‚ by giving men time to grow rich without it.

Many even of what secmed to Tacitus defects of policy, would be merits to an impartial critic ; who, for instance, would hardly be induced to believe that Germanicus, whose chief recorded achievements are those of mere ravage and massacre ⁸, or ostentatious and futile obsequies to the remains of those who fell with Varus ², or at best barren victories in the field ', balanced by disastrous retreats⁸, and entailing untold requisitions on Gaul ¹⁰, was recalled from an all but completed conquest ¹¹.
